│ zext (lshr <2 x i1> %cmp, trunc <2 x i32> %y to <2 x i1>) to <2 x i32>\nThis is        │
│ incorrect because LLVM's shift semantics require the shift amount to be strictly less  │
│ than the bit width of the value being shifted. For an i1 type, any non-zero shift      │
│ amount is invalid and produces poison. In the original IR, shifting i32 by 1 is        │
│ well-defined and results in 0; after the transform, shifting i1 by 1 yields poison.    │
│ Alive2 confirms the target becomes more poisonous than the source.\n\n2. Analyzing     │
│ opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows the first transformation is shrinkType, and the        │
│ resulting IR truncates the shift amount to <2 x i1>. The Alive2 counterexample         │
