│ shifting an i1 by 1 violates the shift constraint. Therefore, shrinkType is applying   │
│ to an LShr without guarding against the shift amount constraint after bitwidth         │
│ reduction.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nshrinkType deliberately handles lshr (and       │
│ bitwise ops) by truncating the non-zext operand to the narrower type and moving zext   │
│ later. This is valid for bitwise logic ops but not generally safe for shift ops unless │
│ we can prove the shift amount is always less than the bit width of the narrowed LHS    │
│ type. The current code only checks known-bits of the result/users but not the legality │
│ of the shift amount for the narrowed type. Consequently, it can produce poison by      │
│ truncating the shift amount to an i1 when the original shift amount was legal for      │
│ i32.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe need to restrict shrinkType for shifts to       │
│ preserve semantics. A conservative and simple fix is:\n- For LShr case, only perform   │
│ the transform if the shift amount is a constant and for every lane the constant is     │
│ strictly less than the bit-width of the narrowed element type (SmallBW). Otherwise,    │
│ bail out.\nThis avoids complicated per-lane non-constant reasoning and guarantees      │
│ legality.\n\nEdit (insert guard right after matching and computing SmallBW):\nAt lines │
