│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                            │
│                                                                                        │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                        │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                            │
│ The transformation performed by VectorCombine::shrinkType turns a logical right shift  │
│ of a zexted value into a shift on the narrower type followed by a zext. In the         │
│ reproducer, it transforms:                                                             │
│   lshr (zext <2 x i1> %cmp to <2 x i32>), %y                                           │
│ into                                                                                   │
│   zext (lshr <2 x i1> %cmp, trunc <2 x i32> %y to <2 x i1>) to <2 x i32>               │
│ This is incorrect because LLVM's shift semantics require the shift amount to be        │
│ strictly less than the bit width of the value being shifted. For an i1 type, any       │
│ non-zero shift amount is invalid and produces poison. In the original IR, shifting i32 │
│ by 1 is well-defined and results in 0; after the transform, shifting i1 by 1 yields    │
│ poison. Alive2 confirms the target becomes more poisonous than the source.             │
│                                                                                        │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                │
│ The debug log shows the first transformation is shrinkType, and the resulting IR       │
│ truncates the shift amount to <2 x i1>. The Alive2 counterexample demonstrates a lane  │
│ where %y is 1: source produces 0; target produces poison because shifting an i1 by 1   │
│ violates the shift constraint. Therefore, shrinkType is applying to an LShr without    │
│ guarding against the shift amount constraint after bitwidth reduction.                 │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ shrinkType deliberately handles lshr (and bitwise ops) by truncating the non-zext      │
│ operand to the narrower type and moving zext later. This is valid for bitwise logic    │
│ ops but not generally safe for shift ops unless we can prove the shift amount is       │
│ always less than the bit width of the narrowed LHS type. The current code only checks  │
│ known-bits of the result/users but not the legality of the shift amount for the        │
│ narrowed type. Consequently, it can produce poison by truncating the shift amount to   │
│ an i1 when the original shift amount was legal for i32.                                │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ We need to restrict shrinkType for shifts to preserve semantics. A conservative and    │
│ simple fix is:                                                                         │
│ - For LShr case, only perform the transform if the shift amount is a constant and for  │
│ every lane the constant is strictly less than the bit-width of the narrowed element    │
│ type (SmallBW). Otherwise, bail out.                                                   │
│ This avoids complicated per-lane non-constant reasoning and guarantees legality.       │
│                                                                                        │
│ Edit (insert guard right after matching and computing SmallBW):                        │
│ At lines 2586-2602 in VectorCombine::shrinkType, add:                                  │
│                                                                                        │
│   // If this is a shift, ensure the shift amount is legal for the narrowed type.       │
│   if (I.getOpcode() == Instruction::LShr) {                                            │
│     // Only proceed if the shift amount is a constant and < SmallBW per lane.          │
│     if (auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(OtherOperand)) {                                  │
│       if (auto *CV = dyn_cast<ConstantVector>(C)) {                                    │
│         for (unsigned Idx = 0, E = CV->getNumOperands(); Idx != E; ++Idx) {            │
│           Constant *CElt = CV->getOperand(Idx);                                        │
│           if (isa<UndefValue>(CElt))                                                   │
│             continue; // undef shift amount is fine                                    │
│           auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(CElt);                                      │
│           if (!CI || CI->getValue().uge(BW))                                           │
│             return false;                                                              │
│         }                                                                              │
│       } else if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(C)) {                                │
│         if (CI->getValue().uge(BW))                                                    │
│           return false;                                                                │
│       } else if (!isa<UndefValue>(C)) {                                                │
│         // Non-int constant kinds (e.g., ConstantExpr) we don't handle here.           │
│         return false;                                                                  │
│       }                                                                                │
│     } else {                                                                           │
│       // Non-constant shift amounts cannot be proven < SmallBW; bail out.              │
│       return false;                                                                    │
│     }                                                                                  │
│   }                                                                                    │
│                                                                                        │
│ This guard ensures we only shrink lshr when the truncated shift amount remains valid   │
│ for the narrower type, preventing the introduction of poison.                          │
│                                                                                        │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                         │
│ The bug stems from shrinking zext across lshr without validating the shift amount      │
│ post-shrink. Adding a guard to allow the transform only when the shift amount is a     │
│ constant less than the narrowed bit width eliminates the miscompile and aligns the     │
│ transformation with LLVM shift semantics. This keeps the optimization for safe cases   │
│ and prevents generating more poisonous IR than the source.                             │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                        │
