  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation performed by
VectorCombine::shrinkType turns a logical right shift of a zexted value into a shift on
the narrower type followed by a zext. In the reproducer, it transforms:\n  lshr (zext <2 x
i1> %cmp to <2 x i32>), %y\ninto\n  zext (lshr <2 x i1> %cmp, trunc <2 x i32> %y to <2 x
i1>) to <2 x i32>\nThis is incorrect because LLVM's shift semantics require the shift
amount to be strictly less than the bit width of the value being shifted. For an i1 type,
any non-zero shift amount is invalid and produces poison. In the original IR, shifting i32
by 1 is well-defined and results in 0; after the transform, shifting i1 by 1 yields
poison. Alive2 confirms the target becomes more poisonous than the source.\n\n2. Analyzing
opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows the first transformation is shrinkType, and the resulting
IR truncates the shift amount to <2 x i1>. The Alive2 counterexample demonstrates a lane
where %y is 1: source produces 0; target produces poison because shifting an i1 by 1
violates the shift constraint. Therefore, shrinkType is applying to an LShr without
guarding against the shift amount constraint after bitwidth reduction.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nshrinkType deliberately handles lshr (and bitwise ops) by truncating the
non-zext operand to the narrower type and moving zext later. This is valid for bitwise
logic ops but not generally safe for shift ops unless we can prove the shift amount is
always less than the bit width of the narrowed LHS type. The current code only checks
known-bits of the result/users but not the legality of the shift amount for the narrowed
type. Consequently, it can produce poison by truncating the shift amount to an i1 when the
original shift amount was legal for i32.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe need to
restrict shrinkType for shifts to preserve semantics. A conservative and simple fix is:\n-
For LShr case, only perform the transform if the shift amount is a constant and for every
lane the constant is strictly less than the bit-width of the narrowed element type
(SmallBW). Otherwise, bail out.\nThis avoids complicated per-lane non-constant reasoning
and guarantees legality.\n\nEdit (insert guard right after matching and computing
SmallBW):\nAt lines 2586-2602 in VectorCombine::shrinkType, add:\n\n  // If this is a
shift, ensure the shift amount is legal for the narrowed type.\n  if (I.getOpcode() ==
Instruction::LShr) {\n    // Only proceed if the shift amount is a constant and < SmallBW
per lane.\n    if (auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(OtherOperand)) {\n      if (auto *CV =
dyn_cast<ConstantVector>(C)) {\n        for (unsigned Idx = 0, E = CV->getNumOperands();
Idx != E; ++Idx) {\n          Constant *CElt = CV->getOperand(Idx);\n          if
(isa<UndefValue>(CElt))\n            continue; // undef shift amount is fine\n
auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(CElt);\n          if (!CI || CI->getValue().uge(BW))\n
return false;\n        }\n      } else if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(C)) {\n
if (CI->getValue().uge(BW))\n          return false;\n      } else if
(!isa<UndefValue>(C)) {\n        // Non-int constant kinds (e.g., ConstantExpr) we don't
handle here.\n        return false;\n      }\n    } else {\n      // Non-constant shift
amounts cannot be proven < SmallBW; bail out.\n      return false;\n    }\n  }\n\nThis
guard ensures we only shrink lshr when the truncated shift amount remains valid for the
narrower type, preventing the introduction of poison.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug stems
from shrinking zext across lshr without validating the shift amount post-shrink. Adding a
guard to allow the transform only when the shift amount is a constant less than the
narrowed bit width eliminates the miscompile and aligns the transformation with LLVM shift
semantics. This keeps the optimization for safe cases and prevents generating more
poisonous IR than the source.",
